#Replacing the null values with region wise median
k=list(df.columns)[:-2]
print(k)
# Imputing for missing values
for i in df[k]:
    if df[i].isnull().sum()==0:
        continue

        
    else:
        replacer=df.groupby('Region')[i].median()  
        for b in df.Region.unique():
            df[i].loc[(df[i].isnull())&(df['Region']==b)]=replacer[b]

Applying K-Means Clustering¶

using Internal validation to report cluster quality and finding optimum number of clusters

In [ ]:
#Elbow Method for finding the optimal no of clusters
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
SSE =[] # Sum of Squared error value are stored here for each possible cluster

for i in range (1,11):
  kmeans_pca = KMeans(n_clusters = i,random_state=42,init="k-means++")
  kmeans_pca.fit(scored_Pca)
  SSE.append(kmeans_pca.inertia_)
In [ ]:
#Plotting the Elbow Graph
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
plt.plot(range(1,11),SSE,marker='o')
plt.title("Elbow Method")
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters")
plt.ylabel("SSE score")
plt.show()

Calculating the Silhoutte score for checking the cluster quality and the validate that k=2 is the right number of clusters

Silhouette Score = (b-a)/max(a,b)

where

a= average intra-cluster distance i.e the average distance between each point within a cluster.

b= average inter-cluster distance i.e the average distance between all clusters.

In [ ]:
#Calculating the Silhoutte score for checking the cluster quality and validate that k=2 is the right number of clusters
kmeans_pca = KMeans(n_clusters = 2,random_state=42,init="k-means++")
y_pred = kmeans_pca.fit(scored_Pca)
score = sklearn.metrics.silhouette_score(scored_Pca, y_pred.labels_, metric='euclidean')
#
# Print the score
#
print('Silhouette Score: %.5f' % score)

Silhouette Score: 0.52342

Calculating Silhoutte Score

In [ ]:
#Plotting the silhouette score with respect to number of culsters to validate once again that cluster quality at k=2 is optimum

from yellowbrick.cluster import SilhouetteVisualizer
 
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(15,8))
for i in [2, 3, 4, 5]:
    
    #Create KMeans instance for different number of clusters
    
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=i, init='k-means++', random_state=42)
    q, mod = divmod(i, 2)
    
   # Create SilhouetteVisualizer instance with KMeans instance Fit the visualizer
    
    visualizer = SilhouetteVisualizer(km, colors='yellowbrick', ax=ax[q-1][mod])
    visualizer.fit(scored_Pca)
    plt.xlabel("Silhoutee cofficent values")
    plt.ylabel("Clusters")

Insight: As we can see from the first graph, the silhouette coefficient score is better for 2 clusters

Calculating the Dunn Index

For clusters, the Dunn index is calculated as:

=min1(,)max1

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import pairwise_distances
from validclust import dunn
kmeans_pca = KMeans(n_clusters = 2,random_state=42,init="k-means++")
y_pred = kmeans_pca.fit(scored_Pca)
dist = pairwise_distances(scored_Pca)
print("The Dunn Value for the clusters is {dunn}".format(dunn = dunn(dist, y_pred.labels_)))# the value of Dunn Index is low because the data is overlapping

The Dunn Value for the clusters is 0.06864681215142851

Calinski_Harabasz_Score

The Calinski-Harabasz index is calculated as:

=1=1 where:

: between-group sum of squares (between-group dispersion) : within-group sum of squares (within-group dispersion) : total number of observations : total number of clusters

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import calinski_harabasz_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
results = {}

for i in range(2,11):
    kmeans_pca = KMeans(n_clusters = i,random_state=42,init="k-means++")
    y_pred = kmeans_pca.fit(scored_Pca)
    db_index = calinski_harabasz_score(scored_Pca, y_pred.labels_)
    results.update({i: db_index})
In [ ]:
#Plotting the CH score for every possible cluster, Higher the value better the cluster performance
plt.plot(list(results.keys()), list(results.values()))

plt.ylabel("Calinski-Harabasz Index")
plt.show()

Silhouette Score

In [ ]:
#Calculating the Silhoutte score for k=2 clusters, as the dendogram clearly shows the optimum number of clusters
clustering_model = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=2, affinity='euclidean', linkage='ward')
y_pred =clustering_model.fit(scored_Pca)
score = sklearn.metrics.silhouette_score(scored_Pca, y_pred.labels_, metric='euclidean')
# Print the score
print('Silhouette Score: %.3f' % score)

Silhouette Score: 0.522

Dunn Index

In [ ]:
#Calculating the Dunn Index, the value of the index is low in heirarchical as well because the data is overlapping 
from sklearn.metrics import pairwise_distances
from validclust import dunn
clustering_model = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=2, affinity='euclidean', linkage='ward')
y_pred =clustering_model.fit(scored_Pca)
dist = pairwise_distances(scored_Pca)
print("The Dunn Value for the clusters is {dunn}".format(dunn = dunn(dist, y_pred.labels_)))

The Dunn Value for the clusters is 0.07545926790719353

Calinski-Harabasz Index

In [ ]:
#calculating the CH Index score,score is higher when clusters are dense and well separated, which relates to a standard concept of a cluster.
from sklearn.metrics import calinski_harabasz_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
results = {}

for i in range(2,11):
    clustering_model = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=i, affinity='euclidean', linkage='ward')
    y_pred =clustering_model.fit(scored_Pca)
    db_index = calinski_harabasz_score(scored_Pca, y_pred.labels_)
    results.update({i: db_index})


plt.plot(list(results.keys()), list(results.values()))
plt.xlabel("Number of clusters")
plt.ylabel("Calinski-Harabasz Index")
plt.show()

Conclusion¶

Conclusion: Hierarchal approach is having a slightly better performance when compared with KMeans as the Internal Validation Metrics have higher values for it, However the countried predicted for each group is same for both the algorithmsand both of the above approaches are giving almost similar results, so using any of the above algorithm is fine to predict the clusters for the given data set.
